    <stitle>DCM AND DDM DRUM TYPE PARKING BRAKE - ROCKWELL DUPLEX CAM MECHANICAL BRAKE - REASSEMBLY</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="2">
        <title>REASSEMBLY</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0402104">Figure 4</hotlnk>for all Item numbers in parentheses.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0402104" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0402104" filename="../figg04/g0402104.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px"/>
            <caption>Figure 4. DCM Brake Exploded View</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. ACTUATOR STRUT</callout1>
                <callout1>2. CAM</callout1>
                <callout1>3. BACKING PLATE</callout1>
                <callout1>4. RETURN SPRINGS</callout1>
                <callout1>5. ACTUATOR LEVER</callout1>
                <callout1>6. NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>7. WASHER</callout1>
                <callout1>8. BRAKE SHOE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Be sure to replace all shoe return springs when overhauling brakes.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If it was removed, install the brake backing plate (Item 3) in the same position. Tighten
                the capscrews to 145 to 175 ft-lbs. (197 to 237 N&#8226;m) for manual transmissions, and 70 to 85
                ft-lbs. (95 to 115 N&#8226;m) for automatic transmissions.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Assemble the cam (Item 2) through the backing plate, install the actuator lever, lockwasher
                and nut (Items 5, 6 and 7). Tighten the nut to give an end play of .001" to .010" as measured with a
                feeler gauge between the backing plate and the lever (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0402105">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0402105" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0402105" filename="../figg04/g0402105.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Actuator Lever Endplay Adjustment</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Be sure to place the brake actuator lever (Item 5) in a neutral (or brake released) position
                        after the endplay adjustment.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install shoe return springs (Item 4) to one end of both shoes. Pivot shoes onto backing
                plate and over anchor pin for side that the return springs are mounted.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Holding shoes in position, slide actuator strut (Item 1) over cam (Item 2) and into shoe
                retaining lance.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Slide actuator strut into shoe retaining lance on the opposite shoe. Pivot shoes to
                remaining anchor pin.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Using a brake spring installer tool, reconnect the remaining return springs (Item 4).</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the brake drum.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Reconnect the driveshaft.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Adjust brake as outlined in
                <hotlnk document="s04021ta_HL0402102.xml" xrefid="hl0402102">ADJUSTMENT</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Burnish parking brake as outlined in
                <hotlnk document="s04021ta_HL0402101.xml" xrefid="hl0402101">BRAKE BURNISHING</hotlnk>.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
